) VALUES (
  '10u-baseball-coaching-guide',
  'coaching',
  'hub',
  '10U Baseball Coaching Guide: Building on the Fundamentals',
  'Complete guide to coaching 10U baseball. Real strategies for developing pitchers, position play, competitive situations, and keeping it fun as the game speeds up.',
  '10U',
  'how to coach 10u baseball',
  'how to coach 10u baseball',
  
  '{"intro":"I learned the hard way that coaching 10U baseball is when things get serious - and I mean that in the best possible way. When I was running camps at the academy, the 10U kids were always my favorites to work with. They''re past the \"where''s first base?\" stage but haven''t hit the attitude years yet. They actually want to get better, and you can see real improvement week to week. But here''s what caught me off guard when I first coached this age group - the parents suddenly think their kid is the next Mike Trout, the games actually matter to the kids, and you''re dealing with real baseball situations that can make or break a season. The good news? This is also when coaching becomes incredibly rewarding. These kids can handle complex instruction, they''re starting to understand strategy, and you can actually work on situational baseball. The challenge is keeping it fun while meeting the increased expectations from everyone involved.","sections":[{"heading":"What Makes 10U Different from 8U","body":"<p>The jump from 8U to 10U is massive, and it''s not just about the pitching - though that''s a big part of it. By 10U, most kids have been hitting off kid pitching for at least a year, so they''re not ducking out of the box anymore. The game speeds up significantly.</p><p>What really changes is the mental side. These kids start keeping their own stats, they know who the best players are, and they''re beginning to understand that baseball isn''t just about participation anymore. I''ve seen 10-year-olds get genuinely upset about making errors or striking out - which means you need to adjust your coaching approach.</p><p><strong>The physical changes are real too.</strong> Some kids hit growth spurts and suddenly they''re throwing harder or hitting the ball farther. Others are still waiting for that development, which creates bigger skill gaps than you had in 8U.</p>","coaching_cues":["Game speed is faster now","Mental mistakes hurt more","Focus on fundamentals still","Competition brings out emotions"]},{"heading":"Position Specialization Starts Here","body":"<p>This is where you stop playing everyone everywhere and start thinking strategically about positions. I used to rotate kids through every position thinking it was \"fair,\" but I learned that putting a kid who''s afraid of the ball at shortstop isn''t doing anyone favors.</p><p>Start identifying your core infielders early - usually your most athletic and confident kids. But don''t lock anyone out completely. I had a kid who couldn''t catch anything in 8U become my starting first baseman in 10U after he grew six inches and gained some coordination.</p><p><strong>The key is being honest with parents about their kid''s development.</strong> That conversation about Johnny not being ready for shortstop? It''s happening whether you initiate it or not. Better to be upfront and focus on what their kid does well.</p>","list_items":["Identify your middle infielders (shortstop, second base)","Find kids with strong arms for third base and catcher","Use outfield for developing players, but don''t dump kids there","First base is perfect for lefties or kids still building confidence"],"coaching_cues":["Athletic kids up the middle","Strong arms at third/catcher","Develop don''t dump"],"common_mistakes":["Playing favorites too obviously","Rotating positions every inning","Not communicating position decisions to parents","Ignoring defensive fundamentals"]},{"heading":"Developing Multiple Pitchers","body":"<p>Here''s where 10U gets tricky - you need more than one or two pitchers, but you also can''t just throw anyone out there. I learned this when my ace got hurt three games into the season and we had nobody else who could throw strikes consistently.</p><p><strong>Start developing at least four pitchers from day one.</strong> Look for kids who can throw strikes, not necessarily the hardest throwers. Control beats velocity every time at this age. I''ve seen too many coaches chase the kid throwing 45 mph while ignoring the one who hits his spots at 38 mph.</p><p>Work on basic mechanics with everyone, but focus your pitching instruction on your core group. Use practice time for live batting practice where your developing pitchers can get real reps without the pressure of game situations.</p>","coaching_cues":["Strikes before speed","Develop four pitchers minimum","Mechanics over velocity","Practice pressure situations"],"common_mistakes":["Overusing your best pitcher","Focusing only on velocity","Not practicing with runners on base","Ignoring pitcher conditioning"]},{"heading":"Practice Structure That Actually Works","body":"<p>Forget the 8U practice where you spent half the time chasing balls and reminding kids which way to run. 10U practices need structure and purpose. These kids can handle 90-minute practices if you keep them moving and engaged.</p><p>I structure practices around stations - usually four stations rotating every 15-20 minutes. Hitting, fielding, pitching/catching, and conditioning or base running. This keeps everyone active and lets you work with smaller groups on specific skills.</p><p><strong>The key insight I learned from high school coaching:</strong> Always end with situational baseball. Work on bunt coverage, rundowns, cutoffs - the stuff that wins and loses games. These kids can handle it, and it''s usually their favorite part of practice.</p>","list_items":["Warm-up and throwing (10 minutes)","Station work - 4 stations, 15 minutes each (60 minutes)","Situational baseball (15 minutes)","Conditioning disguised as games (5 minutes)"],"coaching_cues":["Keep them moving","Small groups work better","End with game situations","Make conditioning fun"],"cta":{"title":"Plan Better Practices","body":"BenchCoach has pre-built practice plans for 10U that keep kids engaged and developing. No more wondering what to do next.","link_text":"Try BenchCoach Free","link_url":"/auth/signup"}},{"heading":"Managing Increased Competition and Emotions","body":"<p>This is where coaching 10U gets real. Kids start crying after strikeouts, parents get more vocal about playing time, and you''re dealing with actual game pressure. I had a kid throw his helmet after making an error, and suddenly I realized we weren''t in recreation league anymore.</p><p><strong>The biggest challenge is balancing competition with development.</strong> These kids want to win - badly - but they also need to keep learning and improving. I learned to talk about \"winning the inning\" instead of just winning the game. It helps them focus on the process.</p><p>Set clear expectations about emotions and sportsmanship from day one. I tell my teams that it''s okay to be upset, but it''s not okay to take it out on teammates, coaches, or equipment. Give kids tools for handling failure - deep breaths, positive self-talk, focusing on the next play.</p>","coaching_cues":["Win the inning first","Process over outcome","Control what you can","Next play mentality"],"common_mistakes":["Ignoring emotional outbursts","Only focusing on winning","Not teaching failure management","Avoiding difficult conversations"]},{"heading":"Handling Parent Expectations","body":"<p>Welcome to the age where parents start thinking their kid might get a scholarship. I''m not kidding - I''ve had parents ask me about travel ball opportunities for their 10-year-old who''s hitting .200. The expectations go through the roof at 10U.</p><p><strong>Communication becomes critical.</strong> I learned to have individual conversations with parents about their kid''s development instead of trying to address everything in team meetings. Some kids are ready for more advanced instruction, others need more fundamental work.</p><p>Be honest but encouraging. That kid who''s struggling at shortstop might be your best outfielder. The player who can''t hit curve balls yet might have great instincts on the bases. Find something positive for every kid, but don''t oversell their current abilities.</p>","list_items":["Schedule individual parent meetings mid-season","Focus on effort and improvement, not just results","Explain your decision-making process","Set realistic expectations for skill development"],"coaching_cues":["Communicate early and often","Focus on growth","Be honest but positive","Address concerns quickly"]},{"heading":"Building Real Team Chemistry","body":"<p>This is when team chemistry actually matters. In 8U, kids are just happy to be there. By 10U, they''re forming friendships, dealing with personality conflicts, and creating the social dynamics that can make or break a season.</p><p>I learned to pay attention to who sits together in the dugout, who celebrates together, and who might be having issues. These kids are old enough to have real conflicts, but young enough that you can usually solve them with a conversation and maybe some strategic partner assignments during practice.</p><p><strong>Create opportunities for bonding outside of games and practice.</strong> Team dinners, movie nights, or even just staying after practice to play catch while parents talk. The teams that genuinely like each other play better baseball.</p>","coaching_cues":["Watch dugout dynamics","Address conflicts early","Create bonding opportunities","Celebrate team successes"]},{"heading":"What Actually Works at 10U","body":"<p>After coaching this age group multiple times, here''s what I''ve learned actually moves the needle: consistent fundamentals practice, clear roles and expectations, and focusing on situational baseball.</p><p><strong>These kids can handle complex instruction now.</strong> You can teach them to read situations, make decisions on the bases, and understand strategy. Use that. Work on bunt defense, covering bases on steals, and backing up throws. This is the fun stuff that makes baseball feel like a real sport.</p><p>Keep stats, but use them as teaching tools. Show kids their improvement over time. Track team stats like on-base percentage or runs scored per inning - metrics that emphasize what you can control.</p>","list_items":["Daily fundamental drills that build confidence","Situational practice with game-like pressure","Clear communication about roles and playing time","Stats that emphasize process over results"],"coaching_cues":["Fundamentals build confidence","Situations win games","Clear roles reduce confusion","Process stats matter most"]}]}',
  ARRAY[]::text[],
  '[{"question":"How much should 10U players be pitching?","answer":"Follow pitch count limits strictly - most leagues cap at 75 pitches per day with required rest. Focus on developing 3-4 pitchers minimum so you''re not overusing anyone. At this age, arm health is way more important than winning games."},{"question":"When should kids start specializing in positions?","answer":"10U is when you can start identifying primary positions, but don''t lock anyone out completely. Focus your best athletes up the middle (catcher, shortstop, second base, center field) but keep developing other kids at multiple positions."},{"question":"How do I handle playing time fairly at 10U?","answer":"Be upfront about your playing time philosophy from day one. Most successful coaches use a merit-based system but ensure everyone gets meaningful opportunities. Communicate individual roles to players and parents - not everyone will start, but everyone should know how they can earn more time."},{"question":"What''s the biggest difference coaching 10U vs younger ages?","answer":"The mental and emotional aspects become huge. Kids start keeping their own stats, comparing themselves to teammates, and dealing with real pressure. You need to coach the person as much as the player - teaching them how to handle failure and success."},{"question":"Should 10U teams focus more on winning or development?","answer":"Both, but development should drive your decisions. Winning becomes important to the kids, so use that motivation to push them to improve. Focus on ''winning'' individual aspects of the game - quality at-bats, making routine plays, good base running decisions."},{"question":"How do I develop team chemistry with 10-year-olds?","answer":"Create opportunities for kids to interact outside of baseball situations. Team dinners, movie nights, or just hanging out after practice while parents talk. Pay attention to dugout dynamics and address personality conflicts early before they become bigger problems."}]',
